all Manor, Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England"},"nl":{"1438–5 November 1492":"1438–5 november 1492","1435–1498":"1435–1498","1460–1552":"1460–1552","1462–Male":"1462–Overleden","1464–Female":"1464–Overleden","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1470–Female":"1470–Overleden","–1506":"–1506","1438–1492":"1438–1492","about 1470":"circa 1470","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","1470":"1470","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","5 November 1492":"5 november 1492","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1498":"1498","1464":"1464","1552":"1552","about 1465":"circa 1465","about 1462":"circa 1462","1506":"1506","1517":"1517","about 1460":"circa 1460","1438":"1438","Woodhall Manor, Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"1438–5 November 1492":"1438–5 November 1492","1435–1498":"1435–1498","1460–1552":"1460–1552","1462–Male":"1462–Deceased","1464–Female":"1464–Deceased","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1470–Female":"1470–Deceased","–1506":"–1506","1438–1492":"1438–1492","about 1470":"about 1470","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","1470":"1470","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","5 November 1492":"5 November 1492","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1498":"1498","1464":"1464","1552":"1552","about 1465":"about 1465","about 1462":"about 1462","1506":"1506","1517":"1517","about 1460":"about 1460","1438":"1438","Woodhall Manor, Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tyrell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Tyrrell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tyrrell","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): perhaps a nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>tirer</i> ‘to pull’, in the same sense as French <i>Tirand</i> ‘one who pulls on the reins’, hence ‘obstinate, stubborn’. This name may have become confused with   Turrell  . A branch of this Anglo-Norman family has been in Ireland since the 12th century. Its name has been Gaelicized as <b>Tirial</b>.","English: habitational name from Tirril (Cumbria), which derives from Old Norse <i>tyri</i> ‘resinous wood’ + <i>erg</i> ‘shieling’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":17,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Tyrell was born in 1438, in Hempstead, Essex, England. She married Sir Thomas de Huntington III in 1458, in Hempstead, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 4 daughters. She died on 5 November 1492, in her hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1438–5 November 1492":"1438–5. november 1492","1435–1498":"1435–1498","1460–1552":"1460–1552","1462–Male":"1462–Surnud","1464–Female":"1464–Surnud","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1470–Female":"1470–Surnud","–1506":"–1506","1438–1492":"1438–1492","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","1470":"1470","1